<p>In a <a href="/wiki/Drum_kit" title="Drum kit">drum kit</a>, <b>splash cymbals</b> are the smallest <a href="/wiki/Accent_cymbal" title="Accent cymbal" class="mw-redirect">accent cymbals</a>. Splash cymbals and <a href="/wiki/China_cymbal" title="China cymbal">china cymbals</a> are the main types of <a href="/wiki/Effects_cymbal" title="Effects cymbal">effects cymbals</a>.</p>
<p>The most common sized splash has a diameter of 10", followed by 8". Most splash cymbals are in the size range of 6" to 13", but some splash cymbals are as small as 4".</p>
<p>Some makers have produced cymbals described as <i>splash</i> up to 22",<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> but a splash of 14" or more is more often described as a <a href="/wiki/Crash_cymbal" title="Crash cymbal">crash cymbal</a>.</p>
<p>Splash cymbals include:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Traditional splash</b> cymbals, medium in weight with little or no <a href="/wiki/Taper_(cymbal)" title="Taper (cymbal)">taper</a>.</li>
<li><b>Rock splash</b> cymbals, heavy but often with a slight taper.</li>
<li><b>China splash</b> cymbals.</li>
<li><b>Salsa splash</b> cymbals.</li>
<li><b>Thin splash</b> cymbals.</li>
<li><b>Bell cymbals</b>.</li>
<li>Specialised <b><i>stack</i> cymbals</b>.</li>
</ul>
<p></p>
